I"Š<p>The level of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/peer-pressure-modulates-autonomic-arousal">arousal</a> influences <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/brains-are-like-forests">functional brain connectivity</a>. This influence leads to changes in the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/continuous-state-dynamical-systems-share-a-common-structure">dynamics</a> of thought. A <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/boltzmann-machine-is-a-universal-learning-machine">sleepy</a> person has a less rigid, more fluid <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/forecasting-framing-renders-neural-emulation-feasible">pattern of thought</a>. Conversely, a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/body-seeks-homeostasis">stressed</a> person is considered to have a rigid, accurate, conventional dynamic. In the context of the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/neural-manifold-folding-explains-explanatory-drive">neural manifold hypothesis</a>, this suggests that metabolic influences alter the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/manifolds-formalize-emergence">manifold structure</a> and vector field. Additionally, this means that one can intentionally modify their current neural dynamics using <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/agitation-can-be-weaponized">voluntary controls of arousal</a> (e.g. through <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/breathwork-modulates-autonomic-arousal">breathwork</a> or <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/optic-flow-modulates-autonomic-arousal">optic flow</a>). In this view, slight <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/boltzmann-distribution-links-macrostates-with-microstate-probabilities">temperature</a> fluctuations affecting the dynamics of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/post-digital-computing-promises-superb-energy-efficiency">neuromorphic</a> computing can be seen as a change in metabolism.</p>
